column1096:
L1. READ: Think of this ladder as representing where people stand in the United States. At the top of the ladder are the people who are the best off — those who have the most money, the most education, and the most respected jobs. At the bottom are the people who are the worst off – who have the least money, least education, and the least respected jobs or no job. 
The higher up you are on this ladder, the closer you are to the people at the very top; the lower you are, the closer you are to the people at the very bottom. Where would you place yourself on the ladder? Please take a moment to pick a rung where you think you stand at this time in your life, relative to other people in the United States.



Assessor Note: Assessor give them a few moments to decide.



READ: Now count starting from the bottom of the ladder to the top. Which number of rung did you place yourself on?
column1097:
L2. READ: Think of this ladder as representing where people stand in their communities. People define community in different ways; please define it in whatever way is most meaningful to you. Where would you place yourself on this ladder. Please take a moment to pick a rung where you think you stand at this time in your life, relative to other people in your community.



Assessor Note: Assessor give them a few moments to decide.



READ: Now count starting from the bottom of the ladder to the top. Which number of rung did you place yourself on?

READ: For this question, please turn to Page 55 in your participant packet. You should see an image of a Rabbit.



(Pause until participant confirms they are on the page with the Rabbit)

 

10a. READ: Think of appearance number 1, was it for a hearing, continuance or court monitoring?

 

Assessor Notes: 

(1) A hearing is when you have to go before a judge so that s/he can decide what is going to happen to you. For example deciding where you are going to live, if you are going to be in detention or do community service, or if the charges against you will be dropped. By the end of the hearing you will know what the judge wants you to do or not do and who is going to take care of you.

(2) A continuance is when you go to court but then you find out that the lawyers or caseworkers need more time to talk about your case. They usually give you another date to come back again when they are ready to decide what is going to happen. 

(3) Court Monitoring is when you have to check in with the judge so s/he can see how you are doing. S/he will ask you some questions to see if you have been doing what you are supposed to or to see how things are going in the place you are living. S/he may also check in with your caseworker, therapist, or probation officer to see if you are doing okay.
